    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <salute>My dear H.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I do not much like the enclosed. They sound to me like truckling to the parsons or to Westminster Abbey.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Ever yours | C. Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">June 22<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
        <div type="enclosure" subtype="other" xml:id="encl.1">
      
          <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Beneath this stone are the remains of Sir Charles Lyell | Author of Principles of Geology<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 
<p rend="centre">Born 1797 | Died 1875.</p> 
<p>The Search of Truth &amp; love of Gods laws manifested in his works was the aim &amp; occupation of his entire life—</p> 
<p rend="centre">or.</p> 
<p>In whatever direction we pursue our researches whether in <hi rend="underline">time</hi> or <hi rend="underline">space</hi>, we discover everywhere the clear proofs of a Creative Intelligence and of His foresight wisdom &amp; powers.</p>
<p rend="right"><hi rend="underline">Principles of Geology<ref target="#foot.f4"/></hi></p>
<p>(<hi rend="underline">too much</hi> &amp; <hi rend="underline">too little</hi>!)</p> 
                </div>
        
    </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10540.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 20 June 1876</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The enclosures are Katherine Murray Lyell’s suggestions for inscriptions on <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3051.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Lyell’s</ref> memorial in Westminster Abbey; Hooker had asked for CD’s views on them (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10540.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 20 June 1876</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10542.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 21 June [1876]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4986.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">C. Lyell 1830–3</ref>. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10540.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 20 June 1876</ref> and n. 2.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">This quotation from <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4986.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">C. Lyell 1830–3</ref>, 3: 384, was repeated in later editions. The original version has ‘power’, not ‘powers’; ‘time’ and ‘space’ are not italicised.</note>
        </div>        
            
